                <head>Putting your TEI markup to work </head>
            </div>
            <div xml:id="h.5mdqvxdkwu1d">
                <head> July 20-24</head>
                <table rend="rules">
                    <row>
                        <cell><hi rend="bold">Monday</hi></cell>
                        <cell><hi rend="bold">Tuesday</hi></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>11-12.30</cell>
                        <cell>11-12.30</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>What do we mean by markup and why do we do it? (LB) [lecture]</cell>
                        <cell>Transcription, critical apparatus and named entities (MT)
                            [lecture]</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>Lunchtime</cell>
                        <cell>Lunchtime</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>14-15.30</cell>
                        <cell>14-15.30</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><p>oXygen: creating a new document; basic manipulations with oXygen
                                (editing, using a schema, transformation for web) (ES) [ex<note
                                    place="comment" resp="Lou_Burnard"><date
                                        when="2015-03-18T11:05:51Z"/><hi
                                        rend="italic normalweight baseline strikethrough smallcaps"
                                        >shd cover everything in my oxygen cheatsheet</hi></note>]
                            </p></cell>
                        <cell>Transcription and entities (MT or ES) [ex]</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>16-17.30</cell>
                        <cell>16-17.30</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>TEI Basics: overview of TEI organisation and core tags<note
                                place="comment" resp="Magdalena_Turska"><date
                                    when="2015-03-18T11:40:56Z"/><hi
                                    rend="italic normalweight baseline strikethrough smallcaps">It
                                    would be good to include drama and verse basics as I will be
                                    using mostly plays for practicals and showcases</hi></note><note
                                place="comment" resp="Lou_Burnard"><date when="2015-03-18T11:06:56Z"
                                    /><hi
                                    rend="italic normalweight baseline strikethrough smallcaps"
                                    >Which plays?</hi></note><note place="comment"
                                resp="Magdalena_Turska"><date when="2015-03-18T11:26:11Z"/><hi
                                    rend="italic normalweight baseline strikethrough smallcaps">I
                                    was thinking something from Bodleian First Folio. Hamlet would
                                    be good except it doesn't have enough places that can be located
                                    on a map, so I'm still looking for a candidate.</hi></note><note
                                place="comment" resp="Lou_Burnard"><date when="2015-03-18T11:30:11Z"
                                    /><hi
                                    rend="italic normalweight baseline strikethrough smallcaps">I
                                    thought we were going to do Guy of Warwick? That has lots of
                                    places and names!</hi></note><note place="comment"
                                resp="Magdalena_Turska"><date when="2015-03-18T11:40:56Z"/><hi
                                    rend="italic normalweight baseline strikethrough smallcaps"
                                    >Let's discuss this face to face</hi></note> with examples (LB)
                            [lecture]</cell>
                        <cell>Visualising your manuscript transcription with TEI BoilerPlate<note
                                place="comment" resp="Lou_Burnard"><date when="2015-03-18T11:37:00Z"
                                    /><hi
                                    rend="italic normalweight baseline strikethrough smallcaps">To
                                    do this properly i will need to see what is being encoded in
                                    their transcriptions well in advance... !</hi></note><note
                                place="comment" resp="Magdalena_Turska"><date
                                    when="2015-03-18T11:37:00Z"/><hi
                                    rend="italic normalweight baseline strikethrough smallcaps">If
                                    you have preference for material (Guy of Warwick perhaps, like
                                    you did in Graz?) we could use it, so you know what to
                                    expect.</hi></note> (LB)</cell>
                    </row>
                </table>
                <table rend="rules">
                    <row>
                        <cell><hi rend="bold">Wednesday</hi></cell>
                        <cell><hi rend="bold">Thursday</hi></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>11-12.30</cell>
                        <cell>11-12.30</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>TEI customization theory and praxis (LB) [lecture]</cell>
                        <cell>TEI Clinic: project-specific queries (all)</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>Lunchtime</cell>
                        <cell>Lunchtime</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>14-15:30</cell>
                        <cell>14-15.30</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><p>OxGarage, Roma &amp; customization [ex] </p><p>Loading TEI texts
                                into TAPAS (ES or MB?)</p></cell>
                        <cell><p>XML Standards family Part 1: CSS, XPath (ES or MB??)
                                [lecture]</p><p>XPath exercise</p></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>16-17.30</cell>
                        <cell>16-17.30</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><p>Creating a digital scholarly edition (MT) [lecture] +
                                    [showcase]<note place="comment" resp="Magdalena_Turska"><date
                                        when="2015-03-17T14:01:12Z"/><hi
                                        rend="italic normalweight baseline strikethrough smallcaps"
                                        >using eXists</hi></note></p></cell>
                        <cell>XML Standards family Part 2: Transforming and extracting data with
                            XSLT (MT) [lecture] + [showcase<note place="comment"
                                resp="Magdalena_Turska"><date when="2015-03-18T11:36:01Z"/><hi
                                    rend="italic normalweight baseline strikethrough smallcaps">-
                                    automatically extracted lists of names- data extraction into
                                    JSON or CSV</hi></note><note place="comment" resp="Lou_Burnard"
                                    ><date when="2015-03-18T11:17:42Z"/><hi
                                    rend="italic normalweight baseline strikethrough smallcaps">They
                                    will have already seen some of this on day 1 (within oxygen) of
                                    course</hi></note><note place="comment" resp="Magdalena_Turska"
                                    ><date when="2015-03-18T11:36:01Z"/><hi
                                    rend="italic normalweight baseline strikethrough smallcaps">Yes,
                                    the 'typical' transforms they will see before. I will
                                    concentrate on showing what XSLT is about going step by step
                                    through creation of simple reading text of a play and then
                                    adding some extra statistics. Then I will follow up on Friday
                                    and will use the same play as input for visualisations with
                                    different javascript libraries (as graph, map etc). And I could
                                    finish with stylometric analysis (split by character) during
                                    last session on Friday.</hi></note>]</cell>
                    </row>
                </table>
                <p>Creating a digital scholarly edition (MT): starting from preparation of TEI
                    source with critical apparatus, showing appropriate XSLT and bundling it all
                    together with eXist.</p>
                <p>XSLT bits:</p>
                <list type="ordered">
                    <item>Reading version of a play</item>
                    <item>Extraction of some structural info into HTML: multi-page document with pbs
                        and @facs, extract a list of pages to be presented as thumbnail image </item>
                    <item>Extract a list of people from a play (eg Hamlet or better something that
                        has more places in it)</item>
                    <item>Extract a list of interactions from a play, export into json and present
                        as a graph?</item>
                </list>
                <table rend="rules">
                    <row>
                        <cell><hi rend="bold">Friday</hi></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>11-12.30</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>TEI Toolkit: overview of display and analytic tools (??)
                            [lecture]</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>Lunchtime</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>14-15.30</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>Playing with JavaScript: d3.js, datatables.js, leaflet.js (MT)
                            [showcase]</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>16-17.30</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>Other packages: R/Stylo, TXM (MB??)</cell>
                    </row>
                </table>
                <p>JavaScript bits (based on the same play as before):</p>
                <list type="ordered">
                    <item>Get list of place names and put it onto a map</item>
                    <item>Fancy table with datatables</item>
                    <item>Network of characters with d3</item>
                </list>
                <p>LB Lou Burnard</p>
                <p>MT Magdalena Turska</p>
                <p>ES Elena Spadini</p>
                <p>MB Misha Broughton</p>
                <p>Comments from Lou :</p>
                <list type="unordered">
                    <item>Where do they do a Roma <note place="comment" resp="Magdalena_Turska"
                                ><date when="2015-03-18T11:31:53Z"/><hi
                                rend="italic normalweight baseline strikethrough smallcaps">Switched
                                order of afternoon sessions on Weds to have space for
                        it</hi></note>exercise? or something practical with customization? Maybe
                        introduce it in the “XML families” session? Or Friday first session?</item>
                    <item>We’d originally proposed the whole of the first afternoon working with
                        oxyGen. Fine to reduce it, but it will be a pretty intense first day.</item>
                    <item>Last day seems a bit vague at the moment</item>
                </list>
            </div>
